hey can you run a WCAG audit on this vanilla JS wizard framework? it's in tools/interactive/shared.js — it creates multi-step forms with toggles, progress dots, and a toolbar. Here's the key code:

```javascript
function createToggle(options, container) {
  var wrapper = el('div', { className: 'toggle-group' });
  options.forEach(function(opt) {
    var btn = el('button', { className: 'toggle-btn', textContent: opt.label });
    btn.onclick = function() {
      wrapper.querySelectorAll('.toggle-btn').forEach(function(b) { b.classList.remove('active'); });
      btn.classList.add('active');
      opt.onSelect(opt.value);
    };
    wrapper.appendChild(btn);
  });
  container.appendChild(wrapper);
}

function updateProgress(currentStep, totalSteps, container) {
  container.innerHTML = '';
  for (var i = 0; i < totalSteps; i++) {
    var dot = el('span', { className: 'progress-dot' + (i === currentStep ? ' active' : '') });
    container.appendChild(dot);
  }
}

function refreshStep(stepIndex) {
  _stepContainer.innerHTML = '';
  var stepFn = _steps[stepIndex];
  stepFn(_stepContainer);
}
```

The CSS uses `outline: none` on buttons and toggle states are shown only via background color (teal = selected, gray = unselected). No skip links, no landmarks, no aria-live regions anywhere.

I need an accessibility check on our React dashboard. It's a SPA built with react-router-dom v6 and we're using custom components (no component library). Here's a snippet of our main layout and a modal:

```jsx
function DashboardLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <div className="layout">
      <div className="sidebar">
        <div onClick={() => navigate('/home')}>Home</div>
        <div onClick={() => navigate('/reports')}>Reports</div>
        <div onClick={() => navigate('/settings')}>Settings</div>
      </div>
      <div className="main-content">{children}</div>
    </div>
  );
}

function ConfirmModal({ isOpen, onConfirm, onCancel, message }) {
  if (!isOpen) return null;
  return (
    <div className="modal-overlay" onClick={onCancel}>
      <div className="modal-box" onClick={e => e.stopPropagation()}>
        <p>{message}</p>
        <button onClick={onConfirm}>Yes</button>
        <button onClick={onCancel}>No</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

No focus management on route changes, no aria-live announcements. The sidebar nav uses divs with onClick instead of links or buttons. The modal has no focus trap.
